\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Every request to the application must specify user identity in some way:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
As part of the request: id=1234 & key=4321, or
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Posting credentials to the login URL
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Requesting to become anonymous by hitting the logout URL
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
By session id - identifying an established login session
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
None of the above, in which case the user is anonymous
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The user identity is made available in a uniform way for use by the rest
 of the application.
 The application may refer to user identity for a number of reasons: e.g.
 to determine authorization or user-specific behaviour (e.g.
 customizations).
 The application should be unaffected if a new authentication method (e.g.
 OpenID) is required.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Terminology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Authentication 
\series bold
protocol
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The means of user authentication and the definition of communication between
 this module and the credential provider.
 Possible protocols include:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
HTTP login
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
AJAX login
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
OpenID
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Active login session
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Per-request authentication
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Logout (an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

unauthentication
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 method which can be treated in this document as an authentication method)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Credential providers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An application that uses this module must provide means of capturing user
 credentials from the end user and suppling them to this module via the
 corresponding 
\series bold
authentication protocol
\series default
.
 In other words each credential provider will use exactly one authentication
 protocol, but there may be multiple users of the same protocol in a single
 application.
\end_layout

